Background: Brewmeisters in Colorado and Texas have teamed up to analyze the relationship between ABV and IBU in each of their states. Use the data sets from the project to help them in their analysis. There three main questions of interest are 1) is there significant linear relationship between AVB (response,y) and IBU (explanatory, x), 2) Is this relationship different between beers in Colorado and Texas and 3) Is there a significant quadratic component in this relationship for either Colorado or Texas or both?

A. Clean and Prepare The Data:

  1. Create column for brewery ID that is common to both datasets similar to what you did in the project, so we can merge!
# Read in beer and breweries data set using _csv for more tidy output
Beers <- read_csv('Beers.csv', col_types = cols())
Breweries <- read_csv('Breweries.csv', col_types = cols())
  1. Merge the beer and brewery data into a single dataframe.
BrewPub <- merge(Beers, Breweries, by.x = "Brewery_id", by.y = "Brew_ID", all = TRUE)
# Change variable names to more meaningful title

BrewPub <- rename(BrewPub, c("Name.x"="Beer","Name.y"="Brewery",
                   "Ounces"="OZ"))
  1. Clean the State Column…get rid of extraneous white space.
trimws(BrewPub$State)
